ly available. Ness spent almost two years in west and northeast Philadelphia to get a sense of how teenage girls experience inflicting physical harm and the meanings they assign to it. While most existing work on girls’ violence deals exclusively with gangs, Ness sheds new light on the everyday street fighting of urban girls, arguing that different cultural standards associated with race and class influence the relationship that girls have to physical aggression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFemale juvenile delinquentszUnited States. 0aInner citieszUnited States. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxPsychology. 0aTeenage girlsxPsychology. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  aCindy.  aFight.  aNess.  aachievement.  aamong.  aareas.  aattain.  aavailable.  ademonstrates.  aearn.  aeasily.  afighting.  agirlhood.  agirls.  akind.  alegal.  amastery.  anecessary.  anormal.  aopportunities.  aotherwise.  apart.  apeers.  apoor.  arespect.  aseen.  aself-esteem.  asense.  asetting.  asocial.  astreet.  athat.  athis.  aurban.  awell.  awhere.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475840340uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814758403.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759073/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK